04889nam a22007455i 9780271092065DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710920657 a10.1515/97802710920652doi  a(DE-B1597)600765  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN3383.S83bP4713 2021 7aLAN0040002bisacsh04a808.2/32231 aPernot, Laurent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Subtle Subtext :bHidden Meanings in Literature and Life /cLaurent Pernot. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (180 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Subtexts All Around Us -- t2 The Rhetoric of Figured Speech -- t3 The Hermeneutics of Suspicion -- t4 Risks and Safeguards of Interpretation -- t5 Greek Pretenses About Rome -- t6 An Ox on the Tongue -- t7 Sexorama -- t8 What About Being Frank? -- t9 Catalog of Further Examples and Practices -- tA Final Word -- tTranslator’s Note on Citations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSubtexts are all around us. In conversation, business transactions, politics, literature, philosophy, and even love, the art of expressing more than what is explicitly said allows us to live and move in the world. But rarely do we reflect on this subterranean dimension of communication.In this book, renowned classicist and scholar of rhetoric Laurent Pernot explores the fascinating world of subtext. Of the two meanings present in any instance of double meaning, Pernot focuses on the meaning that is unstated—the meaning that counts. He analyzes subtext in all its multifarious forms, including allusion, allegory, insinuation, figured speech, irony, innuendo, esoteric teaching, reading between the lines, ambiguity, and beyond. Drawing on examples from figures as varied as Homer, Shakespeare, Molière, Proust, Foucault, and others, as well as from popular culture, Pernot shows how subtext can be identified and deciphered as well as how prevalent and essential it is in human life.With erudition, wit, and intelligence, Pernot explains and clarifies a device of language that we use and understand every day without even realizing it. The Subtle Subtext is a book for anyone who is interested in language, literature, hidden meanings, and the finer points of social relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAllusions in literature. 0aConnotation (Linguistics). 0aSubtext (Drama, novel, etc.). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aHiggins, W. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2021 Englishz978311075406308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2021z9783110753950oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074510840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027109206540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271092065/original  a978-3-11-074510-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075406-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_E